Journal: Well, there are two
main factors at play.

12:53.072 --> 12:57.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The first one is a little bit
tied to what's driving the
falling stock markets worldwide,

12:57.343 --> 13:02.348 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and that's China. China's sort
of always been the golden goose
when it comes to oil markets,

13:02.348 --> 13:07.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
particularly with demand.
China's about the second largest
oil consumer in the world,

13:07.053 --> 13:10.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and so whenever there are
indications that the Chinese
economy perhaps isn't going to

13:10.757 --> 13:13.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be as strong as people had
expected, it causes a great deal
of uncertainty when it comes

13:13.493 --> 13:16.062 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to oil.

13:16.062 --> 13:21.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The second factor is Iran. The
sanctions are about to be lifted
that were imposed by the

13:21.901 --> 13:26.272 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
United States and the European
Union, and once those sanctions
are up, a lot of people

13:26.272 --> 13:29.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
anticipate a significant a
amount of oil coming into the
market from Iran, perhaps as
many

13:29.542 --> 13:33.079 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
this year as 500,000
barrels of oil.

13:33.079 --> 13:37.517 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the market is already
oversupplied, and you're going
to dump additional barrels into

13:37.517 --> 13:42.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the market from Iran. And then
you have problems or questions
about demand that would have

13:42.321 --> 13:46.693 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
been able to bring up the price.
So, there's just a lot of
indicators that are not positive

13:46.693 --> 13:49.529 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
at this time when it
comes to the oil market.

13:49.529 --> 13:53.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, is it,
though, expected that these
countries are just going to
continue

13:53.399 --> 13:57.937 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to pump regardless of how
low the price is going?

13:57.937 --> 14:01.541 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRADLEY OLSON: That's right. I
mean, one of the things that you
see happening when the

14:01.541 --> 14:06.679 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
price goes down is that
everybody's trying to make up
for the lost revenue. And so
this

14:06.679 --> 14:11.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is something that's actually
happened in the history of oil
crashes, is that all the
producers

14:11.050 --> 14:14.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and companies actually try to
pump more oil because they're
trying to make up for whatever

14:14.454 --> 14:18.191 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
they have been losing
by producing more.

14:18.191 --> 14:22.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In this case, a lot of people
expected the U.S. shale
companies and U.S. companies
that

14:22.428 --> 14:26.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were behind a major boon in
production in the last few years
to slow down, and they

14:26.933 --> 14:30.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
just haven't done that yet. They
have been a lot more resilient
than anybody expected.

14:30.570 --> 14:34.140 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Liz Ann Sonders,
you used the word panic a minute
ago. Compare this to what

14:34.140 --> 14:37.343 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was going on in 2008.

14:37.343 --> 14:42.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LIZ ANN SONDERS: Oh, I don't
think this resembles 2008 by any
stretch, when you think about

14:42.515 --> 14:47.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the proximate cause for that, it
was obviously a seizure of the
financial system which had

14:47.320 --> 14:52.425 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
global tentacles and the
leverage associated with that.

14:52.425 --> 14:56.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what we're seeing now is a
bit more concentrated in the
commodity space. Leverage in the
financial

14:56.362 --> 15:01.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
system is significantly lower
than it was back then. I think
what we're seeing has a

15:01.400 --> 15:07.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
greater analogy to 1998 than it
does 2008, where you had an
environment where you had

15:07.540 --> 15:12.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
major currency disruptions,
problems in the emerging
markets.

15:12.245 --> 15:16.315 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It ultimately caused a
tremendous amount of volatility
and even a very severe
correction

15:16.315 --> 15:21.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the U.S. stock market, but it
didn't take the financial system
nor the U.S. economy

15:21.821 --> 15:25.224 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
down with it, and I think that's
the better analogy than 2008.

15:25.224 --> 15:29.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So what does that
mean? You talked about the
psyche of investors and how

15:29.896 --> 15:33.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's changing, and I think you
mentioned millennials. I mean,
what is different about

15:33.099 --> 15:35.935 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the psyche of investors today?

15:35.935 --> 15:40.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LIZ ANN SONDERS: Well, I think
we're well past certainly the
go-go days of the late

15:40.573 --> 15:43.810 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
1990s, where there was the cult
of equities and everybody was
enthusiastic about it, it

15:43.810 --> 15:46.379 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was a hobby for many.

15:46.379 --> 15:52.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You didn't quite build that back
up into 2007. The bubble at that
time was more outside the

15:52.151 --> 15:57.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stock market, in that it was
concentrated in housing. And
those stocks and homes are

15:57.256 --> 16:01.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the two biggest components of
household net worth, so you have
gotten the hit to both

16:01.494 --> 16:06.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of those things, which I think
what we have established,
whether it's millennials as
children

16:06.232 --> 16:10.503 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the baby boomers or even the
older generation after that, is
not all that different than

16:10.503 --> 16:13.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what we saw come out of the
Great Depression, not that this
environment is as extreme as

16:13.005 --> 16:15.508 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

16:15.508 --> 16:21.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it really instituted an era
of deleveraging. And I would
call it a smarter investor,
smarter

16:21.547 --> 16:26.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
consumer. They're not spending
the windfall of these lower oil
prices. Some of it's going

16:26.419 --> 16:29.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to consumption, but some of it
is going to savings and
continued debt pay-down. That's

16:29.755 --> 16:32.491 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the kind of psyche change
I think we're seeing.

16:32.491 --> 16:39.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Bradley Olson,
you mentioned previous oil
market crashes. What's the
history

16:39.332 --> 16:42.435 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
when something like this
happens? How does the price of
oil find its bottom before it

16:42.435 --> 16:45.071 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
starts to rise again?

16:45.071 --> 16:49.075 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRADLEY OLSON: Well, what we see
-- usually, what they say, and
it's sort of an adage that

16:49.075 --> 16:53.379 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
exists in the market, is that
low prices cure low prices.

16:53.379 --> 16:59.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What they mean by that is
whenever companies and even
countries, you know, don't spend

16:59.352 --> 17:04.557 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a lot of money, you will see
that follow the oil market about
a year or two years after

17:04.557 --> 17:09.028 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they stop spending. And so what
we have seen from the past is
that when you have underspending

17:09.028 --> 17:14.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for a year or two that doesn't
come to the level that they need
to spend to increase

17:14.734 --> 17:18.271 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
production or to bring
production to replace all the
oil that they have already put
out

17:18.271 --> 17:20.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into the market, whenever you
see that happening, that's when
the price starts to come back

17:20.473 --> 17:22.541 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
up.

17:22.541 --> 17:28.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Already, the level of spending
is so low in the past two years,
or it's been reduced so

17:28.214 --> 17:32.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
much in the past two years, that
it's already worse than at any
point in any two-year period

17:32.551 --> 17:37.657 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the 1980s. So you already
have the ability to compare this
downturn and this oil and

17:37.657 --> 17:42.762 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
natural gas crash to the worst
of the periods of the 1980s when
it was also very low.

17:42.762 --> 17:48.134 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So you have to go all the way
back to the '70s and the Arab
oil embargo to find a time

17:48.134 --> 17:50.436 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
when the crash was
as bad as it is now.

17:50.436 --> 17:54.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, it's given
us all a lot to, not just think
about. Maybe we all need

17:54.240 --> 17:59.679 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to turn to the history books in
both the markets and the oil
situation.

17:59.679 --> 18:01.447 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Bradley Olson, Liz Ann
Sonders, we thank you both.

18:01.447 --> 18:02.148 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LIZ ANN SONDERS: Thanks, Judy.

18:02.148 --> 18:09.322 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BRADLEY OLSON: Thank you.

18:09.322 --> 18:23.836 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
