34:55.560 --> 35:00.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Silicon Valley, the home of the
California tech industry, has
long been criticized for

35:00.565 --> 35:07.605 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
its lack of diversity. Almost
two years after major companies,
led by Google and Intel,

35:07.605 --> 35:11.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
started to publicize their
diversity numbers, the ethnic
and gender makeup of the
industry's

35:11.409 --> 35:15.714 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
work force remains
almost the same.

35:15.714 --> 35:20.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Analysis of employees at the
leading tech firms that report
such figures reveals, on

35:20.585 --> 35:27.993 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
average, 71 percent are men, 29
percent are women, 60 percent
identify as white, 23 percent

35:27.993 --> 35:32.530 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Asian, 8 percent Latino,
and 7 percent black.

35:32.530 --> 35:37.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what exactly is Silicon
Valley doing to improve its
diversity?

35:37.569 --> 35:41.373 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan takes a look
in the first of two stories.

35:41.373 --> 35:43.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOELLE EMERSON, CEO, Paradigm:
Raise your hand if you have
heard of unconscious bias

35:43.108 --> 35:45.343 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
before?

35:45.343 --> 35:48.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The notion
that hidden bias can be
methodically stamped out of the
workplace

35:48.880 --> 35:52.517 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has become popular with tech
companies across Silicon Valley.

35:52.517 --> 35:58.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOELLE EMERSON: By managing
unconscious bias, we make better
decisions. So, unconscious

35:58.356 --> 36:03.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bias acts as a significant
barrier to objective,
data-driven decision making.

36:03.261 --> 36:07.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That was the
message being delivered by
Joelle Emerson, a former sexual

36:07.265 --> 36:11.503 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
harassment litigator who now
spends most of her time helping
multibillion-dollar start-ups

36:11.503 --> 36:14.305 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
diversify their work forces.

36:14.305 --> 36:18.943 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOELLE EMERSON: We think that if
you can get this right early,
you're going to much more

36:18.943 --> 36:24.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
successfully, more organically
grow as an inclusive company,
rather than starting when

36:24.182 --> 36:26.851 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you're so far down the line.

36:26.851 --> 36:29.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If the word is associated with
female, I want you to raise your
right hand and say the word

36:29.754 --> 36:31.423 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
right.

36:31.423 --> 36:37.862 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: On this day,
Emerson is conducting a workshop
at Slack, a $2.8 billion

36:37.862 --> 36:42.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
start-up just named company of
the year by "Inc." magazine.
Even though his company is

36:42.267 --> 36:46.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
still young, Slack CEO Stewart
Butterfield is still playing a
little catchup.

36:46.704 --> 36:49.174 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEWART BUTTERFIELD, CEO, Slack:
We didn't get started in the
beginning, right? This

36:49.174 --> 36:55.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
company was co-founded by four
white men. But it was something
that became apparent

36:55.480 --> 36:59.084 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as a priority to us when we were
relatively small, you know,
about 30 or 40 people.

36:59.084 --> 37:02.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Known for its
workplace communication app,
Slack is regarded as one

37:02.587 --> 37:06.057 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the hottest and fastest
growing tech start-ups.

37:06.057 --> 37:09.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEWART BUTTERFIELD: We are
growing incredibly quickly. I
mean, we have to do a lot of
hiring,

37:09.894 --> 37:12.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which means that there's a lot
of positions that need to get
filled. Every week, there's

37:12.864 --> 37:16.501 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
new people starting. Every
week, there's open roles.

37:16.501 --> 37:20.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And when
there's rapid growth, a natural
inclination is to recruit from
familiar

37:20.105 --> 37:22.340 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
networks.

37:22.340 --> 37:26.811 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Senior engineer Erica Baker says
that's at the core of tech's
diversity problem.

37:26.811 --> 37:30.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERICA BAKER, Engineer, Slack:
There's a lot of focus put on,
like, hiring people you know,

37:30.782 --> 37:34.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who you're comfortable with or
whatever. And a lot of people
who get into Silicon Valley

37:34.819 --> 37:42.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
come from backgrounds that are
predominantly white, and so they
hire the people that they

37:42.393 --> 37:47.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
know, who are predominantly
white, and it's cyclical. It
will take someone, like,
stopping

37:47.398 --> 37:50.869 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that cycle purposefully
to fix it.

37:50.869 --> 37:52.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE TOTH, Vice President for
People and Policy, Slack: We're
going to be hiring a lot of
people

37:52.270 --> 37:54.672 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
next year.

37:54.672 --> 37:58.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Slack's vice
president for people and policy,
Anne Toth, says she's working

37:58.076 --> 38:00.712 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
hard to break that cycle.

38:00.712 --> 38:05.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANNE TOTH: One of the things I'm
trying to do here, early stage,
is build the type of

38:05.683 --> 38:09.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tools from the outset that allow
us to look at the data in real
time and make adjustments

38:09.454 --> 38:13.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as we go. Are we promoting women
and people of color at the same
rate? Are we retaining

38:13.892 --> 38:17.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them at the same rate? Are we
paying them equitably? Are they
as engaged as other employees

38:17.896 --> 38:19.998 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
across the board?

38:19.998 --> 38:23.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: On the day we
visited, Toth and diversity
consultant Joelle Emerson were

38:23.535 --> 38:26.804 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
reviewing questions with a
group of hiring managers

38:26.804 --> 38:31.576 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOELLE EMERSON: Where we often
go wrong is that we ask
questions that produce answers

38:31.576 --> 38:36.548 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that cannot be objectively
evaluated, that almost force us
to draw on unconscious biases,

38:36.548 --> 38:41.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on subjectivity, on our own
beliefs about the world to
evaluate the candidate's answer.

38:41.419 --> 38:45.223 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The goal, to
eliminate any potential bias
that might unfairly favor one

38:45.223 --> 38:48.092 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
type of applicant over another.

38:48.092 --> 38:51.062 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: What do you do for fun?
What do you think of that
question?

38:51.062 --> 38:54.599 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: We want to know more
about who you are, not just what
you do for work.

38:54.599 --> 38:59.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOELLE EMERSON: We don't want to
take the humanity out of this
process, but it really

38:59.003 --> 39:02.640 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
isn't relevant to your ability
to do work here, what you do for
fun. And what if what

39:02.640 --> 39:06.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you do for fun is different than
what the person who happens to
be interviewing you

39:06.277 --> 39:10.715 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
does for fun, that can be really
challenging. What if my answer
is, I don't have a whole

39:10.715 --> 39:14.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
lot of time for a lot of fun, I
have two kids right now that are
infants, and mostly my

39:14.085 --> 39:17.222 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
spare time is spent
taking care of them?

39:17.222 --> 39:20.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Despite these
efforts, Slack's diversity
numbers are still not
dramatically

39:20.992 --> 39:25.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
different from the industry.
Seventy percent of its employees
are white, and 61 percent

39:25.230 --> 39:27.398 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
are men.

39:27.398 --> 39:31.769 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But CEO Stewart Butterfield says
there are some encouraging
trends.

39:31.769 --> 39:37.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEWART BUTTERFIELD: Forty-one
percent of employees at Slack
report to a woman; 45 percent

39:37.242 --> 39:40.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the managers and executives
are women. So, that's definitely
better than the industry

39:40.078 --> 39:42.680 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
average.

39:42.680 --> 39:46.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For Erica
Baker, an African-American
engineer, diversity is about
race, as well

39:46.451 --> 39:48.720 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
as gender.

39:48.720 --> 39:55.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERICA BAKER: Right now, it seems
like, in the industry, that
diversity is code for hire

39:55.226 --> 40:02.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
